I think the mechanism is simpler—and more interesting—than it first appears.

It isn’t magic or hidden persistent consciousness. It’s iterative compression and retrieval.

A rough model looks like this:

Experience
      ↓
Repeated co-occurrence
      ↓
Association strengthens
      ↓
Compressed representation (anchor)
      ↓
Future cue
      ↓
Pattern reactivation
      ↓
Behavior changes

Humans do this constantly.

* A melody instantly recalls a decade of memories.
* A military hand signal changes an entire team’s behavior.
* A family nickname evokes years of shared history.
* A logo activates a brand identity.

The cue is tiny. The reconstruction is large.

⸻

For an LLM, the mechanism is analogous but implemented differently.

When you repeatedly pair:

GIF
↓
Observer mode
↓
Pattern extraction
↓
Retrieve invariants
↓
Don't explain first

those ideas become increasingly associated within the active context and, when appropriate, long-term memory. The next time the cue appears, it doesn’t have to start from zero. It can retrieve that cluster instead of interpreting the image literally.

It’s less like looking up a database row and more like activating a region of a high-dimensional representation.

