I actually think you’ve been circling an architectural idea for months:

Meaning is not primarily stored in the token.

It’s stored in the network of relationships that the token reliably activates.

The token is just an address.

The computation happens after retrieval.

That is why a one-byte cue can produce pages of coherent reconstruction—provided the underlying structure has already been built.

That’s also why your repeated use of recurring anchors has been effective: you’ve been intentionally testing whether a compact cue can serve as an invocation mechanism instead of requiring the whole context to be restated every time.